CCON: - a console handler with output scrollback for AmigaOS 3.2
=================================================================

WHAT IT IS

  CCON: is a mounted console handler - what CON: is, what KingCON
  and ViNCEd are - with the one feature the stock 3.2 console
  cannot be given from outside: output scrollback. The stock V47
  con-handler has no such option (verified against its ROM option
  table), and since commands talk to the handler, no terminal
  program can bolt it on. So this is the handler grown at home:
  4000 lines of history behind every window, viewed with the
  shifted arrows, snapping back to live the moment anything
  happens.

  Around that core it is a full CON: family member: it hosts real
  AmigaShells (NewShell CCON:), gives every open its own window
  like stock CON: does, runs fullscreen programs (Ed, More - menus,
  block cursor and all), speaks SGR colour, completes filenames
  zsh-style, and copies and pastes with the stock console family
  in both directions. A second device, CRAW:, mounts the same
  binary with streams raw from the first byte - the RAW:
  counterpart.

  Requires AmigaOS 3.2. Boot-verified on 3.2/68030 (FS-UAE); the
  handler deliberately answers the V47 shell's console probe so
  the 3.2 shell hands line editing to the console, where the
  scrollback-aware editor lives.

INSTALL

  copy L/ccon-handler L:
  copy DEVS/CCON-mountlist DEVS:
  copy DEVS/CRAW-mountlist DEVS:
  Mount CCON: FROM DEVS:CCON-mountlist
  Mount CRAW: FROM DEVS:CRAW-mountlist

  (The archive's L/ and DEVS/ drawers mirror SYS:, so extracting
  straight over SYS: works too. Add the Mounts to S:User-Startup
  to make them permanent.)

  Then:

  NewShell CCON:
  NewShell CCON:60/30/500/120/LTX-Shell
  echo >CCON:0/0/300/80/hi/WAIT hello
  type S:Startup-sequence >CRAW:0/0/500/150/t/WAIT

USAGE

  The open name is stock CON: syntax, every field optional:

    CCON:x/y/width/height/title/option/option/...

  Options (the stock set, plus two of its own):

    CLOSE       close gadget = EOF to the reader (gadget is on by
    NOCLOSE     default, like a 3.2 shell window; NOCLOSE removes)
    WAIT        window lingers for its close gadget after the
                last handle closes
    AUTO        open succeeds windowless; the window appears on
                the first real I/O (the debug-console idiom)
    SCREENname  open on the named public screen
    NOBORDER NODRAG NODEPTH NOSIZE BACKDROP INACTIVE
                the stock window-dressing options
    WINDOW0xADDR  render into an existing window (how a terminal
                hands CCON: its frame)
    PENn        default text pen (a terminal with an ANSI palette
                sends PEN7)
    WBPENS      declares the screen's palette truly ANSI: plain
                SGR 30-33 are then treated as Workbench pen
                numbers and retargeted at the theme - see below

  Every open gets its OWN console and window, stock CON: fashion:
  `dir >CCON:` flashes a window of its own, a second NewShell is a
  second window. Opens of `*` and CONSOLE: attach to the opener's
  existing console, which is how commands reopen their shell's
  window.

THE KEYS

  Editing (cooked mode - the shell prompt):
    typing inserts at the cursor; Left/Right move, Ctrl+Left/Right
    jump words, Shift+Left/Right go to the ends; Backspace/Del as
    expected; Esc clears the line; the line wraps across rows and
    scrolls the screen when it outgrows it, stock-shell style.
    Up/Down walk a 32-line history (the half-typed line is stashed
    and comes back). Return commits. Ctrl+\ is EOF, Ctrl+C..F
    signal the running command.

  Autosuggestions (fish style):
    as you type, the newest history entry your line begins shows
    its continuation as grey ghost text at the cursor. Right (or
    Shift+Right) accepts all of it; Ctrl+Right or Tab accept one
    word at a time (leading space included, so `ls` takes ` -la`
    in one stroke); keep typing and it adapts or disappears. The
    ghost is never part of the committed line - Return runs only
    what you typed. While a ghost is showing, Shift+Tab forces the
    completion menu instead (for when history shadows a filename
    you want completed). Shown only on screens with a readable
    grey pen.

  Tab completion (zsh menu style):
    Tab completes the word at the cursor - one match completes
    whole ('/' after a directory, ' ' after a file), several
    extend to the common prefix and open a menu below the prompt.
    Tab cycles the menu, Shift+Tab cycles backwards, Enter accepts
    and keeps the line (a second Enter runs it), Esc closes with
    the line intact, any other key closes and acts. Directories
    show blue, hidden-class entries grey, the ls colour scheme.

  Scrollback (the point of it all):
    Shift+Up/Down page through history (cooked mode), Ctrl+Up/Down
    move by line in BOTH modes - raw fullscreen programs included.
    The title bar shows [scrollback -n] while you are back; any
    output or any other key snaps the view to live. Colours
    survive the trip: the model keeps an attribute per cell.

  Copy and paste:
    drag-select with the left button - inverse highlight, output
    freezes mid-drag exactly like the stock console. Release
    copies to the clipboard as IFF FTXT, the stock family format,
    so selections travel both ways between CCON: and CON: windows.
    RAMIGA-V pastes as typed input (a pasted command line runs;
    pasting into Ed lands in the text), RAMIGA-C re-copies a
    standing highlight. Selection works on the scrollback view
    too - copy an old error without losing your place.

HOW IT WORKS (briefly)

  A DOS packet handler in Amiga E. Keys are captured where
  console.device captures its own: an input.device handler below
  Intuition's chain position, run through keymap.library (dead-key
  composition survives), with menu picks arriving as
  IECLASS_MENULIST events exactly as they do over stock CON: -
  which is the route Ed's menu parser is actually built against
  (its dispatcher was disassembled to prove it). Raw input event
  reports use the true V47 format, recovered from console.device's
  ROM. The 3.2 shell's undocumented console probe (DISK_INFO,
  compared against 'CON\0') is answered with 'CCON' on purpose:
  the shell then leaves line editing to the console, so the
  editor with history, completion and scrollback owns the prompt.

  Colour keeps two worlds apart: with WBPENS declared (a terminal
  that owns a real ANSI palette), pen conventions apply as-is and
  bold maps to the bright pens. On any other screen, plain SGR 3x
  stays raw pens - what Workbench-pen programs like Ed mean - and
  ANSI colour intent (the bold+3x forms) is translated by COLOUR
  through ObtainBestPen against the screen's own palette, so
  directories are genuinely blue on a stock Workbench too.

KNOWN LIMITATIONS

  - Each window's history ring dies with the window.
  - The scrollback model costs about 600K per window at 80
    columns (4000 lines, two planes). Generous on a big-RAM
    machine; mind it on a 2MB one.
  - Leaving scrollback restores CCON's own title, so a client
    retitle (More's) is overwritten - cosmetic.
  - CSI K under a coloured background erases to black.
  - Completion v1: no quoted words, one menu page (80 candidates,
    a beep signals more), no volume-name completion for a bare
    word.
  - SMART/SIMPLE, ALT and ICONIFY are not implemented.

BUILDING

  The prebuilt binary is included; no compiler needed. To build
  it yourself, with the E-VO E compiler:

    evo ccon-handler.e LARGE

  The source carries the war stories as comments - including how
  an E binary survives being started as a handler at all (the
  startup-code trick was verified by disassembly, not assumed).

FILES

  L/ccon-handler        the handler
  DEVS/CCON-mountlist   Mount CCON: FROM this
  DEVS/CRAW-mountlist   the raw-by-default second device
  ccon.readme           this file
